# Gogo Testing, Deployment, And Upgrade Rules

Use this rule when adding tests, changing commands, deploying, upgrading Gogo,
or verifying production readiness.

Framework module: `github.com/cybersaksham/gogo`.

## Testing

- Add focused tests for changed behavior.
- Run app/package tests before broad project tests.
- Use Gogo testing helpers for HTTP clients, settings, databases, fixtures,
  mail, queues, admin assertions, and framework behavior.
- Keep tests independent of production services unless explicitly marked as
  integration coverage.

## Common Commands

Use `go run manage.go <command>` as the explicit Django-style project
entrypoint. The installed `gogo` binary delegates project-aware commands to
`go run manage.go <command>` when it is run from this project, so either form is
valid after the CLI is installed.

| Command | Use for |
| --- | --- |
| `make test` | run project tests |
| `make check` | run project checks |
| `make run` | run the development server |
| `make tidy` | run `go mod tidy` |
| `gogo help`, `gogo --help`, `gogo -h` | list CLI commands |
| `gogo version`, `gogo --version`, `gogo -version` | show version metadata |
| `gogo startproject` | create a Gogo project |
| `gogo <project-aware-command>` | delegate to `go run manage.go <project-aware-command>` inside this project |
| `go run manage.go check` | run settings and system checks |
| `go run manage.go runserver` | run the development server with HTTP routes, API routes, admin, development static/media mounts, middleware registry, and lifecycle hooks |
| `go run manage.go startapp` | create and auto-install a Gogo app |
| `go run manage.go makemigrations` | create migrations |
| `go run manage.go migrate` | apply or roll back migrations |
| `go run manage.go showmigrations` | list migrations |
| `go run manage.go sqlmigrate` | render migration SQL |
| `go run manage.go squashmigrations` | write a squashed replacement migration |
| `go run manage.go optimizemigration` | optimize migrations or report no safe changes |
| `go run manage.go createsuperuser` | create an admin user |
| `go run manage.go changepassword` | change a user password |
| `go run manage.go collectstatic` | collect static files |
| `go run manage.go shell` | open a project shell |
| `go run manage.go dbshell` | open a database shell |
| `go run manage.go test` | run project tests |
| `go run manage.go worker` | run a queue worker |
| `go run manage.go beat` | run the queue scheduler |
| `go run manage.go inspect` | inspect workers |
| `go run manage.go queues` | inspect queues |
| `go run manage.go dumpdata` | dump fixture data |
| `go run manage.go loaddata` | load fixture data |

Generated apps can expose `checks.Check` values through `Checks()` and custom
management commands through `Commands()`. Project wiring passes both into
`management.MainProject`, so app checks run under `go run manage.go check` and
app commands run directly, for example `go run manage.go blog.reindex`.

`go run manage.go runserver` also uses project-level `Middleware`,
`ServerConfig`, `Ready`, and `Shutdown` hooks. Keep readiness checks fast and
deterministic, and use shutdown hooks for cleanup that must run after the server
stops.

For generated project or deployment changes, also run:

```bash
go run manage.go check --deploy
```

## External Integrations

- PostgreSQL integration requires a database URL.
- Redis integration requires Redis connection settings.
- RabbitMQ integration requires RabbitMQ connection settings.
- Report which external integrations were not exercised when verification
  skips them.

## Deployment

- Run web, worker, and beat from the same project version.
- Apply migrations before serving code that depends on new schema.
- Collect static files before deploying static asset changes.
- Keep old application versions available until migrations, workers, beat, and
  smoke tests are verified.

## Upgrades

- Pin `github.com/cybersaksham/gogo` in `go.mod`.
- Read Gogo `CHANGELOG.md` before upgrading.
- Verify generated project behavior after dependency updates.
- Confirm `gogo version` matches the intended framework version.
